First, I pulled in the data from Morningstar Direct. (I combined it using “Combine_Files.r”). There were 24,971 rows and 89 columns. Data was pulled from Morningstar Direct on April 7, 2021.

We use the “Annual Report Net Expense Ratio.” Here’s why.

For the 2019 fee study from Morningstar the analyst says they used the lesser of Annual Report Net Expense Ratio and Annual Report Adjusted for each fund. “… adjusted excludes short interest, reverse repo rates, among other things that make it hard to compare fixed income and alt funds across firms. However, we didn’t JUST use adjusted because it’s not exhaustive of the whole universe we found – a handful of funds had missing adjusted expense ratios, but every one had a net expense ratio.”

Full <- read_csv("data_combined.csv",
                 guess_max = 25000)

I made the following adjustments to the data:

  • Replaced spaces in the column names with periods.
  • Removed fund of funds & money funds
  • Combined the following firms Eaton Vance & Calvert Research and Management, SPDR State Street Global Advisors & "State Street Global Advisors, Nuveen and TIAA Investments
  • Calculated the average assets for 2018, 2019 and 2020.
  • Multiplied the annual average asset figures by the expense ratio (to use later for asset-weighted calculations).
  • Calculated the percent change in net expense ratios from 2018 to 2019 and 2019 to 2020.

20,634 rows, 98 columns Adjusted_Data

Adjusted_Data <- Full %>%
  rename_all(make.names) %>%
  filter(Fund.of..Funds != "Yes",
         US.Category.Group != "Money Market"
         ) %>%
  mutate(
    Firm.Name.Mod = case_when(
      Firm.Name == "SPDR State Street Global Advisors" ~ "State Street Global Advisors",
      Firm.Name == "Calvert Research and Management" ~ "Eaton Vance",
      Firm.Name == "Nuveen" ~ "TIAA Investments",
      Firm.Name %in% c("Harding Loevner", "Third Avenue", "Tweedy, Browner") ~ "AMG Funds",
      Firm.Name %in% "Amundi Pioneer" ~ "Pioneer Investments",
      grepl("AllianzGI", Name) ~ "AllianzGI_",
      TRUE ~ as.character(Firm.Name)
    )
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    Net_Asst_2018_AVG = rowMeans(.[, 47:58], na.rm = TRUE),
    Net_Asst_2019_AVG = rowMeans(.[, 59:70], na.rm = TRUE),
    Net_Asst_2020_AVG = rowMeans(.[, 71:82], na.rm = TRUE),
    Asst_By_Fee_2018 = Net_Asst_2018_AVG * Annual.Report.Adjusted.Expense.Ratio..Year2018,
    Asst_By_Fee_2019 = Net_Asst_2019_AVG * Annual.Report.Adjusted.Expense.Ratio..Year2019,
    Asst_By_Fee_2020 = Net_Asst_2020_AVG * Annual.Report.Adjusted.Expense.Ratio..Year2020,
    Pct_Change_2018_2019 = (
      Annual.Report.Adjusted.Expense.Ratio..Year2019 - Annual.Report.Adjusted.Expense.Ratio..Year2018
    ) / Annual.Report.Adjusted.Expense.Ratio..Year2018 * 100,
    Pct_Change_2019_2020 = (
      Annual.Report.Adjusted.Expense.Ratio..Year2020 - Annual.Report.Adjusted.Expense.Ratio..Year2019
    ) / Annual.Report.Adjusted.Expense.Ratio..Year2019 * 100
  )

write_csv(Adjusted_Data,
          "~/Data/Fee_Data_2021/fee_data_2020/results/MF_Fee_Report_040721_ag.csv")

ACTIVE PRODUCTS

Fund families with the lowest/highes fees across active products

Here I look at the fund families with the lowest and highest overall fees across active products. I filter out index funds and remove fees that are NA (blank) for 2020. 19,199 rows remain.

Additions:

  • Group the data by firm
  • Count how many shareclasses each firm has
  • Sum their net assets 2020

Filter:

  • Firms with at least 50 share classes
  • Firms with at least $25 billion in assets in 2020

13,717 rows remain ActiveFunds

Next steps:

  • Group the data by firm
  • Count how many shareclasses each firm has
  • Sum their adjusted assets (individually) for 2018, 2019 and 2020
  • Sum their net assets (individually) for 2018, 2019 and 2020
  • Divide the total adjusted assets by the total net asssets to calculate asset-weighted fees for each fund shop (individually) for 2018, 2019 and 2020

48 rows Active_Fees

ActiveFunds <- Adjusted_Data %>%
  filter(
    Net_Asst_2020_AVG != 0 &
      Index..Fund != "Yes" &
      !is.na(Annual.Report.Adjusted.Expense.Ratio..Year2020)
  ) %>%
  group_by(Firm.Name.Mod) %>%
  mutate(
    Count = n(),
    Sum_Assets_2020 = sum(Net_Asst_2020_AVG, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  ungroup() %>% 
  filter(Count >= 50 &
           Sum_Assets_2020 >= 2.5e+10
         )

Active_Fees <- ActiveFunds %>%
  group_by(Firm.Name.Mod) %>%
  summarise(
    Count = n(),
    Sum_Assts_Wted_2018 = sum(Asst_By_Fee_2018, na.rm = TRUE),
    Sum_Assets_2018 = sum(Net_Asst_2018_AVG, na.rm = TRUE),
    Fee_Wted_2018 = Sum_Assts_Wted_2018 / Sum_Assets_2018,
    Sum_Assts_Wted_2019 = sum(Asst_By_Fee_2019, na.rm = TRUE),
    Sum_Assets_2019 = sum(Net_Asst_2019_AVG, na.rm = TRUE),
    Fee_Wted_2019 = Sum_Assts_Wted_2019 / Sum_Assets_2019,
    Sum_Assts_Wted_2020 = sum(Asst_By_Fee_2020, na.rm = TRUE),
    Sum_Assets_2020 = sum(Net_Asst_2020_AVG, na.rm = TRUE),
   Fee_Wted_2020 = Sum_Assts_Wted_2020 / Sum_Assets_2020
  )
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
write_csv(Active_Fees,
          "~/Data/Fee_Data_2021/fee_data_2020/results/active/fees_activefunds_firm.csv")

Active_HighFees <- Active_Fees %>%
  arrange(desc(Fee_Wted_2020)) %>%
  top_n(10, Fee_Wted_2020)

Active_LowFees <- Active_Fees %>%
  arrange(Fee_Wted_2020) %>%
  top_n(-10, Fee_Wted_2020)

Active_Summary <- ActiveFunds %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  summarise(
    Count = n(),
    Sum_Assts_Wted_2018 = sum(Asst_By_Fee_2018, na.rm = TRUE),
    Sum_Assets_2018 = sum(Net_Asst_2018_AVG, na.rm = TRUE),
    Fee_Wted_2018 = Sum_Assts_Wted_2018 / Sum_Assets_2018,
    Sum_Assts_Wted_2019 = sum(Asst_By_Fee_2019, na.rm = TRUE),
    Sum_Assets_2019 = sum(Net_Asst_2019_AVG, na.rm = TRUE),
    Fee_Wted_2019 = Sum_Assts_Wted_2019 / Sum_Assets_2019,
    Sum_Assts_Wted_2020 = sum(Asst_By_Fee_2020, na.rm = TRUE),
    Sum_Assets_2020 = sum(Net_Asst_2020_AVG, na.rm = TRUE),
   Fee_Wted_2020 = Sum_Assts_Wted_2020 / Sum_Assets_2020
  ) %>%
  select(
    1,
    3:4,
    6:7,
    9:10
  ) %>% 
  gather(
    key = "Field",
    value, "Count",
    2:7
  )

Fees by Type of Active Fund Category

Here I look at fund families’ fees for each U.S. category types for active funds. I pull in the filtered data from ActiveFunds.

Next steps:

  • Group the data by firm and U.S. category group
  • Sum their adjusted assets (individually) for 2018, 2019 and 2020
  • Sum their net assets (individually) for 2018, 2019 and 2020
  • Divide the total adjusted assets by the total net asssets to calculate asset-weighted fees for each fund shop and category group (individually) for 2019 and 2020
  • Count how many shareclasses there are for each category

Next:

  • Group by firm name
  • Sum total share classes for each fund family
  • Sum total adjusted assets
  • Sum total net assets
  • Calculate average fee for each fund family
  • Calculate percent of assets each fund family has in each category group
Active_Cat <- ActiveFunds %>% 
  group_by(Firm.Name.Mod, US.Category.Group) %>% 
  summarise(
    Asst_Wted_Cat_2018 = sum(Asst_By_Fee_2018, na.rm = TRUE),
    Sum_Assets_Cat_2018 = sum(Net_Asst_2018_AVG, na.rm = TRUE),
    Fee_Wted_Cat_2018 = Asst_Wted_Cat_2018 / Sum_Assets_Cat_2018,
    Asst_Wted_Cat_2019 = sum(Asst_By_Fee_2019, na.rm = TRUE),
    Sum_Assets_Cat_2019 = sum(Net_Asst_2019_AVG, na.rm = TRUE),
    Fee_Wted_Cat_2019 = Asst_Wted_Cat_2019 / Sum_Assets_Cat_2019,
    Asst_Wted_Cat_2020 = sum(Asst_By_Fee_2020, na.rm = TRUE),
    Sum_Assets_Cat_2020 = sum(Net_Asst_2020_AVG, na.rm = TRUE),
    Fee_Wted_Cat_2020 = Asst_Wted_Cat_2020 / Sum_Assets_Cat_2020,
    Cat_Count = n()
  ) %>% 
  group_by(Firm.Name.Mod) %>% 
  mutate(
    ShareClass_Count = sum(Cat_Count, na.rm = TRUE),
    Sum_Assts_Wted_2019 = sum(Asst_Wted_Cat_2019, na.rm = TRUE),
    Sum_Assets_2019 = sum(Sum_Assets_Cat_2019, na.rm = TRUE),
    Fee_Wted_2019 = Sum_Assts_Wted_2019 / Sum_Assets_2019,
    pct_assets_2019 = (Sum_Assets_Cat_2019 / Sum_Assets_2019) * 100,
    Sum_Assts_Wted_2020 = sum(Asst_Wted_Cat_2020, na.rm = TRUE),
    Sum_Assets_2020 = sum(Sum_Assets_Cat_2020, na.rm = TRUE),
    Fee_Wted_2020 = Sum_Assts_Wted_2020 / Sum_Assets_2020,
    pct_assets_2020 = (Sum_Assets_Cat_2020 / Sum_Assets_2020) * 100
    )

write_csv(Active_Cat,
          "~/Data/Fee_Data_2021/fee_data_2020/results/active/cat_activefunds_firm.csv")

Active_Cat_Sum <- Active_Cat %>%
  group_by(US.Category.Group) %>%  
  summarise(
    SHARECLASSES = sum(Cat_Count),
    FEE = round((sum(Asst_Wted_Cat_2020)/sum(Sum_Assets_Cat_2020)),2),
    ASSETS = sum(Sum_Assets_Cat_2020)
    ) %>%  
  mutate(
    pct = round(ASSETS / sum(ASSETS)*100,2)
    )

Lowcost_Active_Firms <- Active_LowFees$Firm.Name.Mod
Highcost_Active_Firms <- Active_HighFees$Firm.Name.Mod

Active_Cat_Pct <- Active_Cat %>%
  select(
    Firm.Name.Mod,
    US.Category.Group,
    Cat_Count,
    Sum_Assets_Cat_2020,
    Sum_Assets_2020,
    Fee_Wted_Cat_2020,
    Fee_Wted_2020,
    pct_assets_2020
  ) %>%
  mutate(Type =
           case_when(
             grepl("Equity", US.Category.Group) ~ "Equity",
             grepl("Bond", US.Category.Group) ~ "Bond",
             TRUE ~ "Other"
           )) %>%
  filter(Firm.Name.Mod %in% Lowcost_Active_Firms |
           Firm.Name.Mod %in% Highcost_Active_Firms) %>%
  group_by(Firm.Name.Mod) %>%
  arrange(-Fee_Wted_2020, .by_group = TRUE)

write_csv(Active_Cat_Pct,
          "~/Data/Fee_Data_2021/fee_data_2020/results/active/cat_activefunds_highlow.csv")

Fee changes among active share classes

Here I am looking at how many active share classes had fees that were cut and hiked as well as saw no change. I start by filtering out non-index funds and fees that are NA (blank) for 2020 and 2019. I also remove fees with a zero expense ratio for 2019 because we can’t calculate change with that base.

Next I create a category (FeeChange) that puts the percent changes (continous) in buckets (categorical). After that I just count the buckets.

Filter:

  • Firms with at least 50 share classes
  • Firms with at least $25 billion in assets
Active_Shareclass <- Adjusted_Data %>%
  filter(
    Annual.Report.Adjusted.Expense.Ratio..Year2019 != 0 &
      !is.na(Annual.Report.Adjusted.Expense.Ratio..Year2019) &
      !is.na(Annual.Report.Adjusted.Expense.Ratio..Year2020) &
      Index..Fund == "No"
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    FeeChange =
      cut(
        Pct_Change_2019_2020,
        breaks = c(-Inf,-0.001, 0, Inf),
        labels = c("Cut", "No Change", "Hike"),
        include.lowest = TRUE,
        right = TRUE
      )
    )

Active_Summary_Shareclass <- Active_Shareclass %>%
  group_by(Firm.Name.Mod,
           FeeChange) %>%
  summarise(count = n(),
    Sum_Assets = sum(Net_Asst_2020_AVG, na.rm = TRUE)
    ) %>%
  group_by(Firm.Name.Mod) %>%
  mutate(
    total_assets = sum(Sum_Assets),
    assets_pct = Sum_Assets / total_assets * 100,
    total_count = sum(count),
    count_pct = count / total_count * 100
  ) %>%
  filter(total_count >= 50 &
           total_assets >= 2.5e+10
         )
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'Firm.Name.Mod' (override with `.groups` argument)
write_csv(
  Active_Summary_Shareclass,
  "~/Data/Fee_Data_2021/fee_data_2020/results/active/shareclass_changes_activefunds.csv"
  )

Fee changes among passive share classes

Here I am looking at how many Passive share classes had fees that were cut and hiked or saw no change. I start by filtering out non-index funds and fees that are NA (blank) for 2020 and 2019. I also remove fees with a zero expense ratio for 2019 because we can’t calculate change with that base.

Next I created a category (FeeChange) that puts the percent changes (continous) in buckets (categorical). After that I just count the buckets.

Filter:

  • Firms with at least 10 share classes
  • Firms with at least $1 in assets
Passive_Shareclass <- Adjusted_Data %>%
  filter(
    Annual.Report.Adjusted.Expense.Ratio..Year2019 != 0 &
      !is.na(Annual.Report.Adjusted.Expense.Ratio..Year2019) &
      !is.na(Annual.Report.Adjusted.Expense.Ratio..Year2020) &
      Index..Fund == "Yes"
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    FeeChange =
      cut(
        Pct_Change_2019_2020,
        breaks = c(-Inf, -0.001, 0, Inf),
        labels = c("Cut", "No Change", "Hike"),
        include.lowest = TRUE,
        right = TRUE
      )
    )

Passive_Summary_Shareclass <- Passive_Shareclass %>%
  group_by(Firm.Name.Mod,
           FeeChange) %>%
  summarise(count = n(),
    Sum_Assets = sum(Net_Asst_2020_AVG, na.rm = TRUE),
    ) %>%
  group_by(Firm.Name.Mod) %>%
  mutate(
    total_assets = sum(Sum_Assets),
    assets_pct = Sum_Assets/total_assets * 100,
    total_count = sum(count),
    count_pct = count / total_count * 100
  ) %>% 
  filter(
    total_count >= 10 &
      total_assets > 0
    )
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'Firm.Name.Mod' (override with `.groups` argument)
write_csv(
  Passive_Summary_Shareclass,
  "~/Data/Fee_Data_2021/fee_data_2020/results/passive/shareclass_changes_passivefunds.csv"
  )

Fee changes among share classes (active & passive)

Here I am looking at how many share classes had fees that were cut and hiked or saw no change.

I start by filtering out fees that are NA (blank) for 2020 and 2019. I also remove fees with a zero expense ratio for 2019 because we can’t calculate change with that base.

Next I create a category (FeeChange) that puts the percent changes (continous) in buckets (categorical). After that I just count the buckets.

Shareclass <- Adjusted_Data %>%
  filter(
    Annual.Report.Adjusted.Expense.Ratio..Year2019 != 0 &
      !is.na(Annual.Report.Adjusted.Expense.Ratio..Year2019) &
      !is.na(Annual.Report.Adjusted.Expense.Ratio..Year2020)
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    FeeChange =
      cut(
        Pct_Change_2019_2020,
        breaks = c(-Inf,-0.001, 0, Inf),
        labels = c("Cut", "No Change", "Hike"),
        include.lowest = TRUE,
        right = TRUE)
    )

write_csv(Shareclass,
          "shareclass_fee_changes.csv"
          )

Summary_Shareclass <- Shareclass %>%
  group_by(Firm.Name.Mod,
           FeeChange,) %>%
  summarise(count = n()
            ) %>% 
  group_by(Firm.Name.Mod
  ) %>% 
  mutate(
    total_count = sum(count)
  )

% change of share class fees from 2019 to 2020

Here I at look how deep firms slashed their expense ratios from 2019 to 2020. First, I removed rows with an expense ratio of zero in 2019 because I can’t calculate changes with that base. I also filter out expense ratios listed as NA (blank) for 2019 and 2020.

Now I need to put the percent change in fees from 2019 to 2020 into buckets. I did that with the cut() function. Here’s a link for personal reference.

Category <- Adjusted_Data %>%
  select(1:20,
         everything()) %>%
  filter(
    Annual.Report.Adjusted.Expense.Ratio..Year2019 != 0 &
      !is.na(Annual.Report.Adjusted.Expense.Ratio..Year2019) &
      !is.na(Annual.Report.Adjusted.Expense.Ratio..Year2020)
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    FeeChange =
      cut(
        Pct_Change_2019_2020,
        breaks = c(-Inf, -50, -25, -10, -1, -0.01, 0, Inf),
        labels = c("< -50", "-25 - -50", "-10 - -25", "-1 - 10", "0 - -1", "0", "> 0"),
        include.lowest = TRUE,
        right = TRUE
      )
  )

write_csv(Category,
          "~/Data/Fee_Data_2021/fee_data_2020/results/shareclass_cuts_total.csv")

Summary_Category <- Category %>%
  group_by(FeeChange) %>%
  summarise(count = n())
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
datatable(Summary_Category)
